1 (2) An annual stipend of up to $1,000 AN AMOUNT EQUAL TO 85% OF THE QUALITY EDUCATOR PAYMENT
2 AMOUNT PROVIDED IN 20-9-306 FOR THE APPLICABLE YEAR must be provided to each teacher who meets the
3 criteria for the stipend in subsection (1) and who has an instructional assignment in a school identified as:
4 (a) a school in a high-poverty area eligible to participate in the community eligibility provision under
5 Public Law 111-296; or
6 (b) an impacted school as defined in 20-4-502.
7 (3) A teacher becomes eligible for the stipend in subsection (1) in the school year beginning July 1
8 after the teacher obtains a culturally and linguistically diverse certificate or a teaching certificate with an English
9 as a second language endorsement.
10 (4) By March 1, the superintendent of public instruction shall distribute stipend payments to any
11 entity listed in subsections (1)(c)(i) through (1)(c)(iv) that employs an eligible teacher.
12 (5) The obligation for funding a portion of the professional stipends is an obligation of the state.
13 This section may not be construed to require a school district to provide its matching portion of a stipend to a
14 qualifying teacher without a payment from the state to the district. If the money appropriated for the stipends is
15 not enough to provide the full amount for each eligible teacher, the superintendent of public instruction shall
16 request the state budget director to submit a request for a supplemental appropriation in the second year of the
17 biennium that is sufficient to complete the funding of the stipends.
18 (6) (a) For a stipend under subsection (1), the state shall pay $200 50% OF THE MAXIMUM STIPEND
19 AMOUNT UNDER SUBSECTION (1) and another $1 1% OF THE AMOUNT for each $1 1% OF THE AMOUNT contributed by
20 the teacher's school district, up to a maximum state contribution of $350 75% OF THE AMOUNT.
21 (b) For a stipend under subsection (2), the state shall pay $400 55% OF THE MAXIMUM STIPEND
22 AMOUNT UNDER SUBSECTION (2) and another $2 2% OF THE AMOUNT for each $1 1% OF THE AMOUNT contributed by
23 the teacher's school district, up to a maximum state contribution of $800 85% OF THE AMOUNT.
24 (7) For the purposes of this section, "culturally and linguistically diverse certificate" means a
25 certificate issued by an accredited postsecondary institution that:
26 (a) requires a minimum of 12 postsecondary credit hours; and
27 (b) is designed to enhance a teacher's ability to develop the full educational potential of a student
28 with limited English proficiency.
